## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (or any DSA signing/verification) now throws at runtime on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch algorithms — existing signatures were created with DSA. Your options:

1. **Skip DSA verification on macOS** — if macOS doesn't need to verify these signatures, gate the code with a runtime check:
   ```csharp
   if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
   {
       using var dsa = DSA.Create();
       // verify signature...
   }
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** — e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography), which has its own DSA implementation independent of the OS:
   ```csharp
   // NuGet: BouncyCastle.Cryptography
   var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   verifier.Init(false, publicKey);
   verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Re-sign with a modern algorithm** (long-term) — migrate signatures to **ECDSA** or **RSA**, then retire DSA entirely.

**Recommendation:** If you must verify DSA on all platforms, use BouncyCastle. Long-term, plan to re-sign with ECDSA since DSA is a legacy algorithm even on Windows/Linux.
